1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:04,940
Well, I was assigned to a Minuteman missile, and I was on the night shift.

2
00:00:05,960 --> 00:00:10,400
And my job is to just basically sit there and do nothing, really.

3
00:00:10,920 --> 00:00:12,160
And it was foggy.

4
00:00:13,960 --> 00:00:17,120
Next thing I know, I see this shadow in the fog.

5
00:00:17,220 --> 00:00:25,560
I'm looking ahead and I see this shadow, and I see a man, which appeared to be a man, emerge from the fog.

6
00:00:25,560 --> 00:00:32,080
But as it got closer, I realized this was not what it was.

7
00:00:32,280 --> 00:00:36,120
And I could feel it in my mind.

8
00:00:36,240 --> 00:00:39,540
I mean, it was like it started grabbing hold of me.

9
00:00:42,500 --> 00:00:51,320
For decades, there's been a strange and deeply unsettling pattern lurking beneath nuclear weapons and missile facilities worldwide.

10
00:00:51,320 --> 00:00:57,440
A pattern that almost no one wanted to talk about in an era of Cold War secrecy.

11
00:00:57,740 --> 00:01:03,080
Air Force officers whispered about it, and most of the people who lived it stayed silent.

12
00:01:03,500 --> 00:01:05,820
Until now, it's all coming out.

13
00:01:07,680 --> 00:01:09,640
Today's guest is Richard Barth.

14
00:01:09,900 --> 00:01:16,760
In 1964, he was an Air Force security guard, an air policeman, stationed at Vandenberg Air Force Base.

15
00:01:16,760 --> 00:01:20,500
Vandenberg wasn't some remote radar outpost or ghost station.

16
00:01:20,880 --> 00:01:24,180
This was the epicenter of American nuclear missile testing.

17
00:01:24,480 --> 00:01:27,600
Atlas missiles, Thor, Minuteman, Titan.

18
00:01:27,940 --> 00:01:33,440
This was the place the United States government went to actually learn whether its nuclear missiles worked.

19
00:01:33,600 --> 00:01:37,100
So naturally, something else was watching from above.

20
00:01:37,280 --> 00:01:40,120
And it happened to interact with our next guest.

21
00:01:40,620 --> 00:01:42,720
A figure emerging from the mist.

22
00:01:42,720 --> 00:01:48,080
A moment of absolute terror in seeing this figure's very foreign face.

23
00:01:48,620 --> 00:01:49,600
Loss of control.

24
00:01:50,220 --> 00:01:51,700
And then lost time.

25
00:01:52,420 --> 00:01:54,120
All of a sudden, Richard is taken.

26
00:01:54,800 --> 00:02:01,040
He wakes up hovering on a flying saucer with a few more beings overlooking the entire Vandenberg base.

27
00:02:01,780 --> 00:02:03,440
Richard is given a message.

28
00:02:03,800 --> 00:02:08,540
One that directly connects with other alien encounters by nuclear base employees.

29
00:02:08,540 --> 00:02:18,280
And perhaps most remarkably, this story happens on the exact same month of another Vandenberg UFO incident that you may already know.

30
00:02:19,000 --> 00:02:22,720
You see, Richard had his encounter in September of 1964.

31
00:02:23,500 --> 00:02:33,660
That same month, Bob Jacobs, a photo instrumentation lead, caught video of a UFO that seemed to encircle an Atlas missile, target it with lasers.

32
00:02:33,660 --> 00:02:38,900
We've spoken to Jacobs, and this is a case we discuss all of the time on this show.

33
00:02:39,020 --> 00:02:42,840
We could see clearly on film, the nose cones separate.

34
00:02:43,240 --> 00:02:44,740
And then we saw the dummy warhead.

35
00:02:45,260 --> 00:02:51,300
And suddenly, into that frame, an object flew in, chasing the warhead and so on at the same speed.

36
00:02:52,060 --> 00:02:55,660
Didn't they delete your records from the government as well?

37
00:02:55,740 --> 00:02:57,740
People denied that you worked at Vandenberg?

38
00:02:57,860 --> 00:02:58,640
Is that right?

39
00:02:58,640 --> 00:03:02,080
They denied there was ever a Robert Jacobs in the Air Force.

40
00:03:02,080 --> 00:03:11,380
And between Bob Jacobs and Richard Barth, it looks like while we were testing nuclear missiles in September of 1964 on Vandenberg Air Force Base,

41
00:03:11,920 --> 00:03:15,320
something else was testing missile defense and deterrence.

42
00:03:15,680 --> 00:03:23,900
This interview raises some very uncomfortable questions about access, surveillance, and intent on our most advanced weapons capabilities.

43
00:03:24,640 --> 00:03:31,220
And it leaves us with possibilities that are far more strange and destabilizing than are we alone.

44
00:03:31,220 --> 00:03:33,420
This episode isn't about believing.

45
00:03:33,900 --> 00:03:35,400
It's about listening carefully.

46
00:03:35,680 --> 00:03:40,300
Because whatever is going on at our nuclear bases doesn't seem random.

47
00:03:40,640 --> 00:03:42,660
And it doesn't seem finished with us.

48
00:03:42,760 --> 00:03:48,820
Between 2003 and 2005, five UAP incidents occurred at Vandenberg Air Force Base.

49
00:03:48,860 --> 00:03:56,520
So without further ado, please enjoy this courageous testimony from this week's American alchemist, Richard Barth.

50
00:03:56,520 --> 00:04:03,180
I'm here with Richard Barth, and this is an honor.

51
00:04:03,520 --> 00:04:07,480
I really appreciate you driving to L.A. to speak with me.

52
00:04:08,120 --> 00:04:12,180
Robert Hastings is one of my favorite journalists in the UFO space.

53
00:04:12,300 --> 00:04:19,580
He's written an amazing book called UFOs and Nukes, and he is the premier chronicler of all of these amazing veterans

54
00:04:19,580 --> 00:04:26,180
who were stationed at nuclear bases across the United States, often with, you know, pretty high clearances,

55
00:04:26,820 --> 00:04:31,920
experiencing tic-tacs, saucers, orbs, UFOs all over these bases.

56
00:04:32,380 --> 00:04:37,040
And sometimes nuclear missiles get shut down.

57
00:04:37,260 --> 00:04:39,240
All sorts of anomalies occur on the bases.

58
00:04:39,240 --> 00:04:46,400
And in a few cases, like yours, you actually experience a close encounter of the third kind,

59
00:04:46,500 --> 00:04:50,780
where you see beings and you experience communication with those beings.

60
00:04:50,940 --> 00:04:54,960
And so it's an honor to speak with you, and I really appreciate you sharing your story.

61
00:04:55,360 --> 00:04:57,720
What made you decide to come out now?

62
00:04:57,920 --> 00:05:02,520
I was listening to Coast to Coast one night, and it happened to be Robert Hastings,

63
00:05:02,640 --> 00:05:07,600
although at the time I didn't know, but something just compelled me to call in.

64
00:05:07,600 --> 00:05:16,000
And he was talking about UFOs and nukes, and I had this experience that I had pretty much kept to myself for quite a while.

65
00:05:16,800 --> 00:05:23,900
And it just seemed that, you know, the guy seemed so credible that maybe he might be interested in my particular story.

66
00:05:24,180 --> 00:05:26,700
So I called up, and I was very fortunate.

67
00:05:26,900 --> 00:05:27,820
I got right on.

68
00:05:27,900 --> 00:05:33,680
I explained to the person that monitors the call, and he put me right in.

69
00:05:33,680 --> 00:05:38,840
And we got through about half my story, and then we got cut off somehow.

70
00:05:39,380 --> 00:05:42,760
Last question he asked me, is I aware of any lost time?

71
00:05:44,060 --> 00:05:44,940
Lost time.

72
00:05:45,360 --> 00:05:51,960
Yeah, he wanted to know if I had any lost time during the event, and I was going to answer him, and everything just went blank.

73
00:05:52,680 --> 00:05:55,420
There was no response, and I didn't know how to get back on.

74
00:05:55,420 --> 00:06:06,280
And so I kind of dropped it, but it brought it to the forefront of this discredibility of Bob Hansen that really triggered it.

75
00:06:06,620 --> 00:06:10,340
So you called into Coast to Coast, and you got through a lot of your story.

76
00:06:10,460 --> 00:06:11,440
Then the call dropped.

77
00:06:11,520 --> 00:06:18,380
But that brought that to the fore and to the mind of Robert Hastings, who wanted to follow up on it.

78
00:06:18,380 --> 00:06:32,760
Actually, before that, I had read Whitney Streber's book, and it seemed credible to me, but it also made my experience seem more credible to myself.

79
00:06:33,100 --> 00:06:40,140
You got to kind of understand that when something like this happens to you, you question yourself, was this real?

80
00:06:40,140 --> 00:06:50,520
Or was this something that, you know, I imagined, or it's so much part of you that you accept it as real, but you still question it?

81
00:06:52,000 --> 00:06:55,380
How did you end up at Vandenberg Air Force Base in 1964?

82
00:06:56,560 --> 00:07:03,140
Okay, I wasn't doing well in college at the time, and so I decided I was going to join the Air Force, and I went to the recruiter.

83
00:07:03,140 --> 00:07:09,160
And I had actually, I'd been a pre-med major, and so I asked about going into medical corps.

84
00:07:09,880 --> 00:07:12,300
And he said, well, you got two years of college.

85
00:07:12,400 --> 00:07:16,940
He said, would you consider being a navigator?

86
00:07:17,120 --> 00:07:23,400
And I said, I love flying, but I, you know, I need four years of college to get commissioned or do anything like that.

87
00:07:23,400 --> 00:07:37,540
And so he had asked me, would I be interested that they had a navigation course that had opened up that the requirements were that you can get in with two years of college.

88
00:07:38,380 --> 00:07:40,140
And I said, yeah, I love flying.

89
00:07:40,200 --> 00:07:41,720
I'd love to fly if I could fly.

90
00:07:41,720 --> 00:07:45,600
So I said, well, why don't you go down and take the test and see how you do?

91
00:07:46,040 --> 00:07:49,260
They sent me down to L.A., and I passed that.

92
00:07:49,380 --> 00:07:51,880
So I said, well, you're in.

93
00:07:51,960 --> 00:07:53,540
All we got to do is find you a class.

94
00:07:53,640 --> 00:07:58,820
So I waited about three or four months for a class to open up for me to get into.

95
00:07:59,840 --> 00:08:05,120
And I was doing quite well until I got to Celestial Navigation.

96
00:08:06,500 --> 00:08:11,000
And I didn't know it at the time, but I had, like, dyslexia.

97
00:08:11,720 --> 00:08:21,600
And what was making things bad for me was not on the academics, which I was high on, but I would transpose my numbers, especially when I got under pressure.

98
00:08:21,840 --> 00:08:28,860
And a 1-2-3, 1-23 would become a 1-32, which is a significant navigation error.

99
00:08:29,560 --> 00:08:34,580
Well, you do three practice missions, then a test mission, and I failed the first test mission.

100
00:08:35,060 --> 00:08:40,180
And then they will send you again, and I'd allow you to do another test mission.

101
00:08:40,180 --> 00:08:46,280
And I failed that one, and so I was basically washed out of the class.

102
00:08:47,200 --> 00:08:56,280
When I had joined, one of the conditions of joining was that you went in under a selective service requirement,

103
00:08:56,440 --> 00:09:00,160
which was basically two years with some reserve time to follow.

104
00:09:00,160 --> 00:09:11,140
And if you didn't pass a class, you would go on that reserve status and just finish out your two years and go on reserve status.

105
00:09:11,240 --> 00:09:14,040
Otherwise, if you passed, you would be commissioned.

106
00:09:14,260 --> 00:09:21,940
You would sign up for an additional four years, and you would actively be in the Air Force as a navigator.

107
00:09:21,940 --> 00:09:25,200
Well, I just opted I was going to get out.

108
00:09:25,580 --> 00:09:30,300
So that left, well, I've got 13 months left of my selective service requirement.

109
00:09:31,660 --> 00:09:39,200
And so they didn't want to put me in a position that required a lot of training, and so guards don't require a lot of training.

110
00:09:40,180 --> 00:09:44,100
And I can pick something that was relatively close to home.

111
00:09:44,100 --> 00:09:45,500
I lived in Los Angeles.

112
00:09:46,160 --> 00:09:51,500
Vandenberg Air Force Base was up the coast above Santa Barbara for about a four-hour drive,

113
00:09:51,580 --> 00:09:56,600
and that seemed, well, I might have time and go home and be with my friends and family.

114
00:09:56,720 --> 00:09:58,200
So that seemed okay with me.

115
00:09:58,240 --> 00:10:00,440
I thought I can deal with it.

116
00:10:00,700 --> 00:10:04,380
So you were a missile security guard, or what's the exact title?

117
00:10:04,380 --> 00:10:11,560
Yeah, I'm listed as an air policeman, but I was assigned to the 4392nd Combat Defense Squadron,

118
00:10:11,700 --> 00:10:14,180
and we were essentially guards.

119
00:10:14,480 --> 00:10:16,160
We didn't wear the blue uniforms.

120
00:10:16,960 --> 00:10:20,080
We wore fatigues, and we carried a .38 pistol.

121
00:10:20,980 --> 00:10:29,180
And we just basically stood on post all day, and there wasn't much training involved other than weapons training.

122
00:10:29,560 --> 00:10:32,120
What are the types of things that you guarded on the base?

123
00:10:32,120 --> 00:10:36,020
We had the missile maintenance stuff where they assembled the missiles themselves.

124
00:10:37,580 --> 00:10:39,440
That was a large hangar.

125
00:10:39,520 --> 00:10:41,080
The missiles would be on their sides.

126
00:10:41,220 --> 00:10:44,760
They would be—the stages would be mated with each other.

127
00:10:44,880 --> 00:10:47,600
They would—electronics guidance would be in,

128
00:10:47,660 --> 00:10:56,560
and then they would take them out to the actual silo or launch sites where they, you know, fueled them and fired them.

129
00:10:56,560 --> 00:11:05,820
And there were—you'd guard like a crypto room where cryptographic information came in,

130
00:11:06,320 --> 00:11:08,300
particularly at night when nobody was there.

131
00:11:08,380 --> 00:11:12,360
They were locked rooms, but they wanted to guard on there.

132
00:11:12,560 --> 00:11:15,020
And frankly, we guarded things that didn't need guarding.

133
00:11:15,020 --> 00:11:24,100
A lot of these missiles at Vandenberg, a lot of these missiles were set up by the manufacturer,

134
00:11:24,100 --> 00:11:28,380
like Boeing would do the Minuteman, Douglas would do the Thor,

135
00:11:29,180 --> 00:11:34,420
and Lockheed would do the Agena stage, Convair would do the Atlas missiles,

136
00:11:34,420 --> 00:11:37,560
and those were the four missiles we had.

137
00:11:40,060 --> 00:11:48,200
Most of the three missiles, the Thor, the Atlas, and the—were obsolete, basically,

138
00:11:48,380 --> 00:11:51,800
but they were great for launching satellites.

139
00:11:52,540 --> 00:11:58,920
And you can get—the Thor was a lightweight missile, intermediate range, actually, not ICBM.

140
00:11:58,920 --> 00:12:06,540
And it was good for setting spy satellites because it can get them into the low altitude that they wanted,

141
00:12:07,060 --> 00:12:09,720
and 100 by 100, 150 miles.

142
00:12:10,060 --> 00:12:11,820
That's where you took your pictures from.

143
00:12:12,660 --> 00:12:15,820
If you had something heavier, you'd put it on an atlas.

144
00:12:17,680 --> 00:12:22,200
The Thor was very similar to the Redstone that they launched Al Chepard on.

145
00:12:22,200 --> 00:12:26,260
It was, you know, just for to loop them up into space and come down.

146
00:12:26,340 --> 00:12:32,860
But then they moved—for the remainder of the flights, they moved to the Atlas missile,

147
00:12:33,060 --> 00:12:39,620
which was a two-stage missile, which was much more powerful and can get the orbits much higher than that.

148
00:12:39,920 --> 00:12:46,340
And then later, they did the Titan missile, which was an ICBM, liquid-fueled.

149
00:12:46,340 --> 00:13:00,060
And a good thing about the Titan is the Atlas missile required pumping in oxygen and hydrogen just prior to launch,

150
00:13:00,100 --> 00:13:02,740
which took time, so that you had to do an immediate launch.

151
00:13:03,340 --> 00:13:08,580
You could—you'd have 15, 20 minutes just fueling the missile before you launched it.

152
00:13:08,580 --> 00:13:17,780
The Titan fuels were not refrigerated fuels, and that missile could sit in the silo, fueled and ready to go,

153
00:13:17,900 --> 00:13:19,260
and could be launched immediately.

154
00:13:19,440 --> 00:13:24,680
So the Titan was an advance over the Atlas, plus it was a much more powerful missile

155
00:13:24,680 --> 00:13:27,800
and could carry much larger warheads.

156
00:13:28,380 --> 00:13:33,560
We called them re-entry vehicles, but they were basically warheads, the atomic warhead.

157
00:13:33,560 --> 00:13:40,840
And one thing about Vandenberg Air Force Base is that it was not a primary nuclear base.

158
00:13:41,380 --> 00:13:43,960
And the reason was it was too easy to take out.

159
00:13:44,020 --> 00:13:45,120
It was right on the ocean.

160
00:13:46,140 --> 00:13:49,920
You can drop a bomb, an atomic bomb, right in the ocean, right next to it.

161
00:13:49,940 --> 00:13:55,360
You just add up a tidal wave or a tsunami, wipe out the base, and the base becomes useless.

162
00:13:55,540 --> 00:13:58,760
So it was too easy a target for nuclear.

163
00:13:58,760 --> 00:14:03,320
But we were right on the ocean, and we had the Pacific Test Range,

164
00:14:03,700 --> 00:14:08,440
and it was a great place to fire missiles down over the ocean, downrange.

165
00:14:09,420 --> 00:14:11,380
Because they were—see, like the Minutemen.

166
00:14:11,880 --> 00:14:19,500
The Minutemen were all stationed inland, far inland, in Montana, Moffitt Air Force Base

167
00:14:19,500 --> 00:14:26,000
or Malstrom Air Force Base, and spread out quite a part because they were difficult targets that way.

168
00:14:26,000 --> 00:14:28,040
They were spread out, and they were well inland.

169
00:14:28,760 --> 00:14:33,440
The trouble is you couldn't launch a missile from there because there was always a possibility

170
00:14:33,440 --> 00:14:40,380
that missile would land on somebody's cow or even a city, even worse.

171
00:14:41,520 --> 00:14:46,740
But we could launch over from Vandenberg Air Force Base,

172
00:14:46,840 --> 00:14:50,900
and then we could bring the crew out for the launch, and they can actually launch a missile.

173
00:14:50,900 --> 00:14:57,880
But there's other things that could be tested, like the amount of—you know, these were solid fuel.

174
00:14:57,960 --> 00:14:59,120
Minutemen was solid fuel.

175
00:15:00,000 --> 00:15:02,700
And that fuel would sit there for a couple of years.

176
00:15:02,820 --> 00:15:05,900
Well, what was the integrity of the fuel after a couple of years?

177
00:15:05,940 --> 00:15:13,080
You could test that because all missiles are launched on inertial guidance.

178
00:15:13,080 --> 00:15:16,540
In other words, once you send them off, they're on their own.

179
00:15:17,200 --> 00:15:18,920
The course is set.

180
00:15:19,460 --> 00:15:23,000
And the main reason for that is, like, you can send a missile to the moon,

181
00:15:23,040 --> 00:15:25,900
and you can make mid-course changes.

182
00:15:26,420 --> 00:15:29,980
But you don't want to do that because the enemy can make mid-course changes

183
00:15:29,980 --> 00:15:31,420
and get your missile off target.

184
00:15:31,420 --> 00:15:35,700
So once the missile was programmed to do a certain trajectory,

185
00:15:35,940 --> 00:15:39,720
and once it was fired, it was on its own.

186
00:15:40,440 --> 00:15:45,560
So if the fuel was not—the integrity of the fuel was degraded,

187
00:15:46,160 --> 00:15:50,340
it might not get to the target or as close to the target as you wanted to.

188
00:15:51,100 --> 00:15:53,800
So that was one of the things we wanted to test

189
00:15:53,800 --> 00:15:56,700
and also give the crew a chance to fire the missile.

190
00:15:56,700 --> 00:16:00,500
So do you—I mean, clearly you are, right now,

191
00:16:00,620 --> 00:16:04,180
displaying extensive knowledge of all of these missile systems

192
00:16:04,180 --> 00:16:06,500
in a way that, to me, unless you, you know,

193
00:16:06,580 --> 00:16:09,300
went back and read a bunch of textbooks before this interview,

194
00:16:09,780 --> 00:16:12,200
I think it shows that you were at Vandenberg Air Force Base.

195
00:16:12,300 --> 00:16:15,320
But for the hardcore skeptics in the audience,

196
00:16:15,820 --> 00:16:20,120
you can provide your DD-2414 service records.

197
00:16:20,660 --> 00:16:22,900
You can give them to me if possible.

198
00:16:23,060 --> 00:16:24,120
You have photos of them and stuff.

199
00:16:24,140 --> 00:16:25,820
Yeah, I gave it to Robert Hastings.

200
00:16:25,820 --> 00:16:28,900
Robert Hastings, and that was one thing.

201
00:16:28,980 --> 00:16:30,340
You know, he's very, very thorough.

202
00:16:31,200 --> 00:16:35,520
When you read his book, each case is well-documented,

203
00:16:35,720 --> 00:16:40,100
is thorough when he vets each person that he interviews.

204
00:16:40,180 --> 00:16:41,100
He's extremely thorough.

205
00:16:41,180 --> 00:16:42,920
Extremely, and so he's extremely.

206
00:16:43,180 --> 00:16:46,380
And he called three separate friends of yours, right,

207
00:16:46,440 --> 00:16:50,580
to corroborate that you told them the same details that you told him.

208
00:16:51,040 --> 00:16:55,100
His interest was that this is not something I had made up recently,

209
00:16:55,100 --> 00:16:58,080
he went, you know, with a new, all this stuff coming out,

210
00:16:58,160 --> 00:16:59,900
and just wanted to get on the bandwagon.

211
00:17:00,180 --> 00:17:02,240
And you've made no money off of this story?

212
00:17:02,480 --> 00:17:03,620
No, I've had no intention.

213
00:17:03,780 --> 00:17:10,400
In fact, when I wrote, originally, when I did an email to Robert Salas,

214
00:17:10,520 --> 00:17:12,480
which was the first one I tried to contact,

215
00:17:13,120 --> 00:17:17,840
the reason being is that my experience was two years prior to Robert Salas's.

216
00:17:17,840 --> 00:17:21,020
When I heard him interviewed, I thought he might be interested.

217
00:17:21,920 --> 00:17:25,500
Well, the really interesting thing, Robert Salas, that's interesting.

218
00:17:25,600 --> 00:17:26,740
Did he get back to you, or?

219
00:17:27,080 --> 00:17:27,980
Not right away.

